Patrick G
Brampton, Canada219 contributions
So beautiful yet needs some love!!!
Mar 2019 ‚Ä¢ Family
Halong Bay is so beautiful but I believe Coron Philippines is much more beautiful. The limestone islands are incredible and so worth the visit. Peak season can be a zoo!!! Literally thousands of people visit this place every day and you can see what this does to its environment. We booked the tour from our hotel in Hanoi and got the full day trip. If you want a relaxing tour go for two days if you have the time. I saw no need to pay any extra charges for a tour as everyone will basically see the main sites. It‚Äôs a good 4 hours drive with a pit stop at a factory that sells marble statues to beautiful hand crafted art pieces. Our boat was quite nice with an upper deck. Food was not bad but if you‚Äôre a big eater you won‚Äôt get full. Drinks are for sale on the boat. Sad to see garbage floating in the bay while sailing through the islands. First stop you can kayak or ride a paddled boat into a secluded cove entering through a big gap in the limestone. Cool to see the monkeys. The next stop is a huge and I mean massive cave! I‚Äôve been to many caves but this was impressive. Easy steps to get upto and a wooded floor that guides you around the cave. The view upon exiting the cave is fabulous as you see the bay from high up. The last stop is a small island where you can actually swim or climb the island peak. Then the boat ride back is nice as sunset photo ops are great. It‚Äôs quite a long day and you arrive back in Hanoi around 9ish. Well worth the visit. Please don‚Äôt litter üòÄ
Written April 7, 2019
Bronwyn L
Endeavour Hills, Australia26 contributions
3
Conflicted
Mar 2019
This place was stunning, amazing and spectacular- and compared to the chaos of Hanoi and Saigon, sitting on the top deck of a cruise boat in the middle of the bay was relatively peaceful. BUT looking at the smog, the rubbish floating by in the water, the hundreds of boats in the bay belching smoke, the hordes of tourists being herded from one place to another and the excess of concrete commercialised construction happening, I wonder how long this place can survive? As much as I was awed by the wonders of nature I was saddened by how humans can exploit such a beautiful area to the extent that they are likely to ruin it.
